Categorize each of the following research questions as "good" or "bad", and provide alternative formulations for the bad ones.

What is the 1994 rate of juvenile delinquency in the U.S.?
Good - question is specific and can be answered numerically (but it's a very simple question that won't require much research)

What can we do to reduce juvenile delinquency in the U.S.?
Good.  Initial research would be needed to establish data on juvenile delinquency, then testing of variables.  Some data should be available

Does education play a role in reducing juvenile delinquents' return to crime?
Good - questions is specific and can be answered numberically (by establishing correlation of education to recidivism)

How many customers does AT&T currently serve in Washington, DC?
Good - question is specific and be answered numerically.  It's a very simple question that won't require much research, more details might be ascertained about those customers. 

What factors lead consumers to choose AT&T over other service providers?
Good, but broad.  Would need to gather a lot of data on AT&T, other service providers, and the customers to identify variables. 

How can AT&T attract more customers?
Good. Initial research would be needed on AT&T customers and enrollment.

Why did the Challenger Shuttle explode?
Bad - question is too broad, can't be answered numerically

Which genes are associated with increased risk of breast cancer?
Good - question is specific and dats should be available

Is it better to read to children at night or in the morning?
Bad - speculative.  No data is available.  

How does Googleâ€™s search algorithm work?
Bad - speculative and broad